  "prompt": "How do current transformers work?",
  "response": "Current transformers (CTs) work based on the principle of electromagnetic induction. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Basic Operation\n- CT consists of a primary winding (main conductor) and secondary winding\n- Primary winding carries the actual current to be measured\n- Secondary winding is wound around a magnetic core\n\n2. Electromagnetic Induction\n- Current in primary winding creates a magnetic field in the core\n- This magnetic field induces a proportional current in the secondary winding\n- The induced current is scaled down to a standard level (typically 5A or 1A)\n\n3. Key Components\n- Magnetic core (usually made of silicon steel)\n- Primary conductor passes through core center\n- Secondary winding wrapped around core\n\n4. Scaling\n- Number of secondary winding turns determines the current ratio\n- Allows measurement of high currents safely at low, standardized levels\n\n5. Applications\n- Electrical protection systems\n- Power metering\n- Current monitoring in electrical networks\n- Instrumentation and control systems\n\n6. Advantages\n- Electrical isolation between high-voltage circuits and measurement equipment\n- Safe current measurement\n- Precise current transformation\n\nCurrent transformers enable safe and accurate current measurement in electrical systems.",
